 a contract with Mott’s, a subsidiary of Dr. Pepper Snapple Group.The company is looking to slash wages by as much as $2.50 an hour for each and every employee, and is trying to take away the workers’ pension plans.','http://www.unionvoice.org/solidarite/notice-description.tcl?newsletter_id=29643770: http://rwdsu.info/en/archives/4/stop-dr-pepper-snapple-taking-money-out-workers-pockets-41010.html:http://www.wnylabortoday.net/news/2010/04/15/southern-tier-councils/the-retail-wholesale-and-department-store-union-rwdsu-united-food-commercial-workers-ask-working-people-for-help-to-stop-dr.-pepper-snapple-from-taking-money-out-of-pockets-of-its-williamson-new-york-workforce/',NULL),(37624,NULL,1614,2994,'DPS has policies in place throughout all aspects of their operations to ensure the safety of their employees in their facilities and on their routes.','http://www.drpeppersnapplegroup.com/about/corporate/workplace-environment/',NULL),(37625,NULL,1614,2989,'DPS has an Ethical Sourcing Code of Conduct. This code is based on the Ethical Trading Initiative, which has established internationally recognized standards covering employee working conditions.','http://www.drpeppersnapplegroup.com/about/corporate/ethical-sourcing/',NULL),(37626,NULL,1614,2981,'No Deviation',NULL,NULL),(37627,NULL,1651,2980,'On April 19, 2010 over 300 members of RWDSU Local 220 have voted to authorize a strike if no agreement can be reached with Mott’s, for workers at the company’s Williamson, New York, facility.  Mott’s is looking to make drastic cuts to workers wages and pensions. The union rejected an offer made to them by Mott’s and sought to continue bargaining.  Mott’s refused and even threatened to cut worker’s wages if their final offer was not accepted.  The union has filed unfair labor practices with the National Labor Relations Board over the company’s conduct.','http://rwdsu.info/en/archives/4/mott%E2%80%99s-workers-authorize-strike-company-refuses-negotiate-41910.html',NULL),(37628,NULL,1614,3058,'In 2008, the Plano headquarters office recycled nearly 240 tons of paper, exceeding its 2007 total by 25%. Recycling and conservation efforts saved 4,000 trees; 876,900 pounds of lumber; nearly 2,600 barrels of oil; 971,700 kilowatt hours of energy. DPS containers are 100% recyclable. More than half of the aluminum used in their cans is post-consumer.','http://www.drpeppersnapplegroup.com/about/corporate/environmental-sustainability/',NULL),(37629,NULL,1614,2971,'DPS is working to replace existing cold drink equipment (coolers and vending machines) with new Energy Star-rated equipment that will save customers nearly $9 million annually in electric costs by 2012. The environmental impact of these efforts equates to removing the CO2 emissions of 11,000 cars from the road each year or planting 16,000 acres of CO2-absorbing forest land.  However, they are ranked # 468 out of 500 in newsweeks list of greenest companies.','http://www.drpeppersnapplegroup.com/about/corporate/environmental-sustainability/:http://greenrankings.newsweek.com/companies/top500/dr+pepper',NULL),(37630,NULL,1614,2991,'Each year DPS give on average about $4 million in cash donations and more than $500,000 in product donations and employee volunteer time.  Employee-driven volunteer, sponsorship and fund-raising initiatives have benefited the local efforts of organizations such as Habitat For Humanity, MS Society, Children’s Miracle Network, Juvenile Diabetes Research Foundation ,and a wide range of local community groups.','http://www.drpeppersnapplegroup.com/about/corporate/community-investment',NULL),(37631,NULL,1614,3008,'In a growing number of plants, DPS  is replacing empty package water rinsers with air rinsers, saving approximately 10,000 gallons per line per day at each site.  However, there is concern about the new Victorville plant in California\'s Mojave Desert.  The facility will use hundreds of millions of gallons of water a year from a water-scarce area to supply soft drink