norganic pesticides.','http://www.saraleefoodservice.com/Products/Beverages/HotTea/BlackTea.aspx',NULL),(42407,NULL,3006,3140,'Company information does not indicate the use of non inorganic fertilizers.','http://www.saraleefoodservice.com/Products/Beverages/HotTea/BlackTea.aspx',NULL),(42408,NULL,3006,3144,'No Deviation',NULL,NULL),(42409,NULL,3006,3146,'Company information does not indicate the use of child labor or slave labor.','http://www.laborrights.org/search/node/pickwick%20tea',NULL),(42410,NULL,3006,3150,'Company information does not indicate that supplies are purchased from Small Cooperatives or Single Farmers.',NULL,NULL),(42411,NULL,3006,3153,'Pickwick Tea is a brand of Sara Lee.  53 Sara Lee companies have violations of safety and health regulations, reported workplace fatalities/catastrophic incidents or have high rates of lost-time workplace injuries and illnesses since 2000.This company has a 2005 injury rate of 8.18 per 100 employees, which is above the national average (2.4 per 100 employees) for that year. Sara Lee Bakery Group in Phoenix, Arizona has been recognized by The Safety and Health Achievement Recognition Program (SHARP) administered by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA). However  Sara Lee Garments, according to workplace medical experts, employees at Sara Lee garment supplier Monclova International in Mexico, are “incapable of doing their work due to the irreversible harm caused by workplace injuries.” In an August 11, 2006 press conference, three women spoke out against worker violations in the textile factory. Workers cited 10 hour workdays, significant decreases in salaries though production levels increased, and the lack of medical assistance as examples of labor violations. Lauro Presqueira, General Manager of Monclova International, stated, “We are confident that all reasonable measures have been identified and implemented” to minimize workplace injuries.\" ',':http://www.workingamerica.org/jobtracker/index.cfm?appState=localSafetyViolation&sortToggle=DESC&zipCode=&companyName=sara%20lee&stateSelect=&zipRadius=100&industry=&start=51http://www.osha.gov/dcsp/smallbusiness/sharp_sites.html#Alabama : http://www.knowmore.org/wiki/index.php?title=Sara_Lee_Corp. :http://www.workingamerica.org/jobtracker/index.cfm?zipCode=&companyName=&industry=&appState=companyDetails&sortToggle=DESC&companyid=2036017',NULL),(42412,NULL,3006,3157,'No Deviation',NULL,NULL),(42413,NULL,3006,3161,'While there is no direct information connecting Sara Lee to abusive working conditions, Sara Lee Scored The Lowest (27%) On Oxfam\'s Grading Of  4 Major Coffee Roasters In 2003, their report states that Sara Lee has performed the worst of the major roasters in almost every aspect of dealing with the coffee crisis. It buys some Fair Trade Certified™ coffee in the US but has no plans to expand in other countries. Sara Lee is falling behind the other roasters. ','http://www.knowmore.org/wiki/index.php?title=Sara_Lee_Scored_The_Lowest_%2827%25%29_On_Oxfam%27s_Grading_Of_The_4_Major_Coffee_Roasters_In_2003',NULL),(42414,NULL,3006,3162,'No Deviation',NULL,NULL),(42415,NULL,3006,3166,'No Deviation',NULL,NULL),(42416,NULL,3006,3170,'No Deviation',NULL,NULL),(42417,NULL,3006,3173,'Earthgrains Baking Companies, Inc., a subsidiary of Sara Lee, reached a $5.25 million settlement with the Department of Justice and the EPA for committing the \"largest ever corporate-wide violations of stratospheric ozone protection regulations.\" Of the 67 facilities run by Earthgrains, 57 leaked refrigerants at a rate 35% higher than allowed by law. In addition, the company made no attempt to correct leakage problems even after their discovery. Refrigerants such as chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) are known to be a major cause of ozone layer depletion.\" (U.S. Department of Justice, 07/31/2003) ','http://www.knowmore.org/wiki/index.php?title=Sara_Lee_Corp.',NULL),(42418,NULL,3006,3176,'Three Sara Lee salespeople have admitted to wrongly assisting Royal Ahold efforts to falsely inflate revenues by signing confirmation letters that gave inflated rebate numbers.\" (Washington Post, April 8, 2003) ','http://www.knowmore.org/wiki/index.php?title=Sara_Lee_Corp.',NULL),(42419,NULL,3006,3181,'No Deviation',NULL,NULL),(42420,NULL,3006,3182,'In May 2002, Sara Lee agreed to pay $3.5 million to 139 black employees who complained of racial harassment and retaliation at Sara Lee subsidiary Hygrade Food Products Corp., a hot-dog plant that closed in 2001. The settlement came after 23 separate racial discrimination suits were filed in June 2001 by African-American employees against the company. The suits, filed in U.S. District Court, alleged that the African-American employees of the Philadelphia Ball Park brand hot dog factory were harassed, subjected to racial epithets, and denied promotions. The suit claimed that white employees received word-of-mouth notice about promotions and transfers.1','http://www.knowmore.org/wiki/index.php?title=Sara_Lee_Agrees_To_Pay_%243.5_Million_To_Black_Employees',NULL),(42421,NULL,3006,3186,'Sara Lee pled guilty to two misdemeanor counts in connection with a listeriosis outbreak that led to the deaths of at least 21 consumers who ate Ball Park Franks hot dogs and other meat products. One hundred people were seriously injured. The company paid a $200,000 fine. In 2005, and 2007 Sara Lee issued recalls for products that may have contained metal fragments, undeclared milk products and potential listeria contamination.  ','http://google2.fda.gov/search?q=sara+lee+inc&x=0&y=0&client=FDAgov&proxystylesheet=FDAgov&output=xml_no_dtd&sort=date%253AD%253AL%253Ad1&site=FDAgov-Recalls-Safety: http://www.knowmore.org/wiki/index.php?title=Ball_Park_Franks_Fiasco:_21_Dead%2C_%24200%2C000_Fine',NULL),(42422,NULL,3006,3189,'The American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees (AFSCME), which controls 8,424 Sara Lee shares wants the corporation to allow shareholders input on issues of executive pay. Although stocks fell, CEO Brenda Barnes’s salary rose from $883,333 in 2004 to $1 million in 2005. Her bonuses rose from $425,392 in 2004 to $1.14 million in 2005. The AFSCME proposal calls for shareholders to vote and approve the “Compensation Discussion and Analysis” section of the proxy each year.','http://www.knowmore.org/wiki/index.php?title=Sara_Lee_Corp.',NULL),(42423,NULL,3006,3193,'Pickwick Teas are available worldwide','http://www.pickwicktea.com/',NULL),(42424,NULL,3006,3197,'No Deviation',NULL,NULL),(42425,NULL,3006,3200,'On several Sara Lee web sites, the company muses about how consumers are likely to mistakenly believe that many “whole grain” breads are actually more like whole wheat bread than white bread, and chides its competitors for not being “100-percent whole-grain.” Yet Sara Lee helps foster that confusion by marketing a “Soft & Smooth Made with Whole Grain White Bread” and falsely claiming that it is as nutritious as whole wheat bread. Today the nonprofit Center for Science in the Public Interest served the company with formal notice that it will file suit against the company if the misleading claims continue. ','http://www.cspinet.org/new/200712171_print.html',NULL),(42426,NULL,3006,3204,'Sara Lee pled guilty to two misdemeanor counts in connection with a listeriosis outbreak that led to the deaths of at least 21 consumers who ate Ball Park Franks hot dogs and other meat products. One hundred people were seriously injured. The company paid a $200,000 fine. In 2005, and 2007 Sara Lee issued recalls for products that may have contained metal fragments, undeclared milk products and potential listeria contamination.  ','http://google2.fda.gov/search?q=sara+lee+inc&x=0&y=0&client=FDAgov&proxystylesheet=FDAgov&output=xml_no_dtd&sort=date%253AD%253AL%253Ad1&site=FDAgov-Recalls-Safety: http://www.knowmore.org/wiki/index.php?title=Ball_Park_Franks_Fiasco:_21_Dead%2C_%24200%2C000_Fine',NULL),(42427,NULL,3006,3208,'Pickwick brand uses fre